---
import BaseHead from '../../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import AffiliateDisclosure from '../../components/AffiliateDisclosure.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../../consts';

const pageTitle = `TinyPNG vs Squoosh: Best Free Image Compressor in 2026 — ${SITE_TITLE}`;
const pageDescription = 'We compared TinyPNG and Squoosh side by side to find the best free image compressor in 2026. Read our hands-on review, comparison table, and final recommendation.';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} articleSchema={{headline: pageTitle, description: pageDescription, datePublished: '2026-05', authorName: 'Toolwise Team'}} />
		<style>
			.review-wrap {
				max-width: 760px;
				margin: 0 auto;
				padding: 40px 24px;
				min-height: calc(100vh - 200px);
			}
			.review-wrap h1 {
				font-size: 2.2em;
				margin-bottom: 12px;
				line-height: 1.2;
			}
			.meta {
				font-size: 14px;
				color: rgb(var(--gray));
				margin-bottom: 28px;
			}
			.intro {
				font-size: 18px;
				line-height: 1.8;
				color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
				margin-bottom: 32px;
				padding-bottom: 24px;
				border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
			}
			.review-wrap h2 {
				font-size: 1.5em;
				margin-top: 40px;
				margin-bottom: 16px;
				color: rgb(var(--black));
			}
			.review-wrap h3 {
				font-size: 1.2em;
				margin-top: 28px;
				margin-bottom: 12px;
				color: rgb(var(--black));
			}
			.review-wrap p,
			.review-wrap li {
				font-size: 17px;
				line-height: 1.8;
				color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
			}
			.review-wrap ul {
				margin-bottom: 16px;
				padding-left: 24px;
			}
			.review-wrap li {
				margin-bottom: 8px;
			}
			.review-wrap a {
				color: var(--accent);
				text-decoration: underline;
			}
			.compare-table {
				width: 100%;
				border-collapse: collapse;
				margin: 20px 0 32px 0;
				font-size: 15px;
			}
			.compare-table th,
			.compare-table td {
				padding: 12px 14px;
				border: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
				text-align: left;
			}
			.compare-table th {
				background: rgb(var(--gray-light));
				font-weight: 600;
				color: rgb(var(--black));
			}
			.compare-table td {
				background: var(--card-bg);
			}
			.compare-table tr:nth-child(even) td {
				background: rgba(var(--gray-light), 0.4);
			}
			.winner-box,
			.runner-box,
			.budget-box {
				border-radius: 12px;
				padding: 24px;
				margin-bottom: 16px;
			}
			.winner-box {
				background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.1), rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.05));
				border: 1px solid rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.3);
			}
			.runner-box {
				background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(92, 124, 255, 0.1), rgba(92, 124, 255, 0.05));
				border: 1px solid rgba(92, 124, 255, 0.3);
			}
			.budget-box {
				background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(245, 166, 35, 0.1), rgba(245, 166, 35, 0.05));
				border: 1px solid rgba(245, 166, 35, 0.3);
			}
			.winner-box h3,
			.runner-box h3,
			.budget-box h3 {
				margin-top: 0;
				font-size: 18px;
			}
			.winner-box h3 { color: #22c55e; }
			.runner-box h3 { color: var(--accent); }
			.budget-box h3 { color: #f5a623; }
			.pick-label {
				display: inline-block;
				font-size: 12px;
				font-weight: 700;
				text-transform: uppercase;
				letter-spacing: 0.5px;
				padding: 4px 10px;
				border-radius: 6px;
				margin-bottom: 8px;
			}
			.winner-box .pick-label { background: #22c55e; color: white; }
			.runner-box .pick-label { background: var(--accent); color: white; }
			.budget-box .pick-label { background: #f5a623; color: white; }
			.cta-inline {
				display: inline-flex;
				align-items: center;
				gap: 6px;
				padding: 10px 20px;
				background: var(--accent);
				color: white;
				font-weight: 600;
				border-radius: 8px;
				text-decoration: none;
				margin-top: 8px;
				transition: all 0.2s ease;
			}
			.cta-inline:hover {
				background: var(--accent-dark);
				transform: translateY(-1px);
			}
			.faq-item {
				margin-bottom: 20px;
			}
			.faq-item h4 {
				font-size: 17px;
				margin-bottom: 6px;
				color: rgb(var(--black));
			}
			.faq-item p {
				margin: 0;
			}
			@media (max-width: 720px) {
				.review-wrap {
					padding: 32px 16px;
				}
				.review-wrap h1 {
					font-size: 1.7em;
				}
				.compare-table {
					font-size: 13px;
				}
				.compare-table th,
				.compare-table td {
					padding: 10px;
				}
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<div class="review-wrap">
			<h1>TinyPNG vs Squoosh: Best Free Image Compressor in 2026</h1>
			<p class="meta">Published May 19, 2026 · Image Tools · 5 min read</p>

			<p class="intro">
				Large images are the number one cause of slow websites. Whether you are a web developer optimizing a portfolio, a blogger trying to rank on Google, or a designer sending files to clients, image compression is essential. The two most popular free tools in this space are <strong>TinyPNG</strong>, the veteran with over a billion images compressed, and <strong>Squoosh</strong>, Google's open-source challenger. We put both to the test.
			</p>

			<h2>Quick Comparison</h2>
			<table class="compare-table">
				<thead>
					<tr>
						<th>Feature</th>
						<th>TinyPNG</th>
						<th>Squoosh</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Price</strong></td>
						<td>Free (up to 20 images)</td>
						<td>Completely free</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Paid Plan</strong></td>
						<td>Web Pro: $39/year</td>
						<td>None (100% free)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Formats</strong></td>
						<td>PNG, JPEG, WebP</td>
						<td>PNG, JPEG, WebP, AVIF, JXL</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Max File Size</strong></td>
						<td>5 MB per image</td>
						<td>No limit (browser-based)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Batch Upload</strong></td>
						<td>Up to 20 at once</td>
						<td>One at a time</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>API Access</strong></td>
						<td>Yes (paid)</td>
						<td>No</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Desktop App</strong></td>
						<td>Photoshop plugin</td>
						<td>No (browser only)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Open Source</strong></td>
						<td>No</td>
						<td>Yes (Apache 2.0)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Our Rating</strong></td>
						<td>★★★★☆ 4.8</td>
						<td>★★★★☆ 4.6</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<h2>TinyPNG Review</h2>
			<p>
				TinyPNG has been the gold standard for lossy image compression since 2013. Its magic lies in selectively reducing the number of colors in an image, a technique that typically reduces file sizes by 50–80% with virtually no visible quality loss. Over 1 billion images have been compressed through the service, and it remains the top choice for web developers who need to optimize entire sites quickly.
			</p>
			<p>
				The workflow is dead simple: drag up to 20 PNG or JPEG files into the browser window, wait a few seconds, and download the compressed versions. For power users, TinyPNG offers a Photoshop plugin and a developer API that integrates directly into build pipelines. The Pro plan removes the 20-image limit and adds Dropbox integration, making it a solid choice for agencies and design teams.
			</p>

			<h3>Pros</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Exceptional compression ratio</strong> — Consistently achieves 60–80% file size reduction while keeping images visually identical to the originals.</li>
				<li><strong>Batch processing</strong> — Upload and compress up to 20 images at once, a huge time-saver for web developers optimizing entire galleries.</li>
				<li><strong>Developer-friendly API</strong> — The REST API integrates seamlessly with CI/CD pipelines, WordPress, and custom build tools.</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Cons</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Limited format support</strong> — Only PNG, JPEG, and WebP. No AVIF or JPEG XL, which are the next-generation formats.</li>
				<li><strong>Free tier limits</strong> — The 20-image cap and 5 MB file limit can be restrictive for professional workflows.</li>
			</ul>

			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Web developers, bloggers, and designers who need to compress many PNG/JPEG images quickly with predictable, high-quality results.</p>

			<a href="https://tinypng.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored" class="cta-inline">
				Try TinyPNG Free →
			</a>

			<h2>Squoosh Review</h2>
			<p>
				Squoosh is Google's open-source image compression app, built by the Chrome DevRel team to showcase next-generation web technologies. Unlike TinyPNG's black-box approach, Squoosh gives you a visual side-by-side comparison and granular control over every compression setting. Want to squeeze an extra 10% out of your image by adjusting chroma subsampling? Squoosh lets you do that.
			</p>
			<p>
				The standout feature is support for cutting-edge formats like AVIF and JPEG XL, which offer significantly better compression than WebP. Squoosh runs entirely in your browser — no uploads to a server — making it ideal for sensitive images. The open-source nature means the underlying codecs are available for integration into your own projects. However, the single-image workflow and steep learning curve make it less suited for bulk operations.
			</p>

			<h3>Pros</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Next-gen format support</strong> — AVIF and JPEG XL compression delivers smaller files than WebP, future-proofing your images.</li>
				<li><strong>Visual comparison + full control</strong> — Side-by-side preview with sliders for quality, effort, and advanced codec options.</li>
				<li><strong>Privacy-first</strong> — Everything happens locally in your browser; images are never uploaded to a server.</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Cons</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>One image at a time</strong> — No batch upload means optimizing a gallery takes significantly longer.</li>
				<li><strong>Overwhelming for beginners</strong> — The sheer number of codec options and technical parameters can confuse casual users.</li>
			</ul>

			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Developers and advanced users who want maximum compression with next-gen formats, or anyone handling sensitive images that should not leave their computer.</p>

			<a href="https://squoosh.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored" class="cta-inline">
				Try Squoosh Free →
			</a>

			<h2>Our Editor's Picks</h2>

			<div class="winner-box">
				<span class="pick-label">Winner</span>
				<h3>🏆 TinyPNG — Best Overall</h3>
				<p>
					For 99% of users, TinyPNG is the better choice. Its batch processing, proven compression quality, and simple workflow make it the most practical tool for everyday image optimization. The API access is a game-changer for professional web developers who need automation.
				</p>
				<a href="https://tinypng.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored" class="cta-inline">
					Try TinyPNG →
				</a>
			</div>

			<div class="runner-box">
				<span class="pick-label">Runner Up</span>
				<h3>🥈 Squoosh — Best for Advanced Users</h3>
				<p>
					If you need AVIF support, work with sensitive images, or want pixel-level control over compression settings, Squoosh is unbeatable. It is completely free with no restrictions — just be prepared to process images one by one.
				</p>
				<a href="https://squoosh.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored" class="cta-inline">
					Try Squoosh →
				</a>
			</div>

			<div class="budget-box">
				<span class="pick-label">Budget Pick</span>
				<h3>💰 Squoosh — Best Free Option</h3>
				<p>
					You cannot beat free with no limits. Squoosh delivers professional-grade compression at zero cost, with the added bonus of keeping your images on your own device. For students and hobbyists, this is the clear budget winner.
				</p>
				<a href="https://squoosh.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored" class="cta-inline">
					Open Squoosh →
				</a>
			</div>

			<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

			<div class="faq-item">
				<h4>Does image compression reduce quality?</h4>
				<p>
					Both TinyPNG and Squoosh use "lossy" compression, which does remove some data. However, the reduction is optimized to be virtually invisible to the human eye. In our tests, compressed images were indistinguishable from originals at normal viewing sizes. For maximum quality retention, Squoosh offers lossless options as well.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="faq-item">
				<h4>Which format should I use: JPEG, PNG, WebP, or AVIF?</h4>
				<p>
					Use <strong>JPEG</strong> for photographs, <strong>PNG</strong> for images with transparency or text, <strong>WebP</strong> for modern web projects (30% smaller than JPEG), and <strong>AVIF</strong> for maximum compression (50% smaller than JPEG) if browser support is not a concern. Squoosh lets you compare all formats side by side.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="faq-item">
				<h4>Can I compress images without uploading them?</h4>
				<p>
					Yes — Squoosh processes everything locally in your browser, so your images never leave your computer. TinyPNG requires uploading to their servers, though they delete files after compression and use secure connections. For sensitive medical, legal, or personal images, Squoosh is the safer choice.
				</p>
			</div>

			<p style="margin-top: 40px; font-size: 14px; color: rgb(var(--gray));">
				<em>Disclosure: This review contains affiliate links. We may earn a commission if you purchase through these links, at no extra cost to you. All opinions are our own based on hands-on testing.</em>
			</p>

			<AffiliateDisclosure />
		</div>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
